Ford GoBike System Data Dataset Exploration¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing users and trips data for approximately 170,999 trips in September 2019 in San Francisco,US.

#Groups ages in clusters: bins = [18, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 120] labels = ['18-29', '30-39', '40-49', '50-59', '60-69', '70+'] bike_2019_09['age_grouped']= pd.cut(bikes['member_age'], bins, labels = labels,include_lowest = True)

#Transform objects in datetime and checks: bike_2019_09['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_2019_09.start_time) bike_2019_09['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(bike_2019_09.end_time)

Sorting the variables in proper types.

In [80]:
# sorts the variables in proper types
ordinal_var_dict = {'weekdays_start': ['Monday','Tuesday','Wednesday','Thursday','Friday','Saturday','Sunday']}

nominal_var_dict = {'user_type': ['Customer','Subscriber'],
                    'member_gender': ['Female', 'Male', 'Other'],
                    'age_grouped':['18-29', '30-39', '40-49', '50-59', '60-69', '70+']}


for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    bikes[var] = bikes[var].astype(ordered_var)

for var in nominal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = nominal_var_dict[var])
    bikes[var] = bikes[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

After a previous wranging data, there are 170999 bike trips with 13 features:
-Time of trip: duration_sec, duration_sec_log, duration_sec_sqrt,duration_sec_cbrt, start_time,end_time,duration_sec_log;
-Weekdays: weekdays_start;
-Ids: bike_id;
-stations: start_station_name, end_station_name;
-User: user_type, member_gender, member_age, age_grouped;
-Other: bike_share_for_all_trip.

Weekdays is a categorical ordinal variable,user_type, member_gender, and age_grouped are categorical nominals, and the oder variables are numericals.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm most interested in figuring out the customer profile.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that age and gender can affect usertype and duration of trips. I also want to discover the trends of use of the bike during the weekdays by type of user.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I have noticed that the gender female has no outliers in informing the date of birth, hence the age.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I a previous stage of data wrangling, I have dropped columns of the stations (coordinates), and I created columns of age, age group and weekdays.
The distance seems not to be a good variable, because we don't know the routes used. These distances in a straight line, as calculated here, do not match reality. Another weakness here is that some trip starts and finish in the same place after a long time-trip.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I have sorted the variables and droped variables I decided do not use in this work. I compare random samples in function of member_age with bike_share_for_all_trip and duration_sec_log with member_age (using 500 samples)using lmplot. And analysed the correlation between the numerical variables of member_age and duration_sec_log using pairplot and using lmplot (with 500 random samples). I compared age member (grouped) across weekdays and duration of trips, considering trips until 30 minutes and longer. I Compared a categorical variable with two numericals with facegrid.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The older the member who shares the bike for the entire trip, the longer the trip. Subscriber users are a bit older than the customers. The correlation among member age and duration_sec_log does not present any interesting result. There are less longer trips, specially in workdays. The duration of trip by younger people is more stable than the older, these have higher variation. Strangely, the behavior of 70+ change on Wednesdays and om Fridays.
